I noticed that the related Eclipse platform bug 158100 "Sending suspend events too quickly causes wrong thread to be selected" recently got a patch (for handleResume() and handleSuspend() in org.eclipse.debug.internal.ui.viewers.update.ThreadEventHandler). I tried that patch and noticed that CDT 3.1.1 and GDB still doesn't work any better with respect to debugging multi-threaded programs and switching threads. However, if CDT follows the way described in 158100 the problem can be solved:

"... when a step is initiated (doesn't matter which thread) all threads are resumed. The thread selected when the step is requested sends a resume with STEP detail. All the rest of the threads are resumed with UNSPECIFIED detail. When the debuggee has finished stepping I send a series of suspends. The first suspend with STEP_END is sent for the thread that is considered the stopping thread. I then send a suspend UNSPECIFIED for all the other threads."

In order to do so in CDT as well, in CThread.resumedByTarget() we must issue DebugEvent.UNSPECIFIED instead of DebugEvent.CLIENT_REQUEST for all threads except the current thread, i.e. the line "events.add( createResumeEvent( DebugEvent.CLIENT_REQUEST ) );" should be replaced with "events.add( createResumeEvent( DebugEvent.UNSPECIFIED ) );", see snippet below:

if ( isCurrent() && detail != DebugEvent.CLIENT_REQUEST && detail != DebugEvent.UNSPECIFIED ) {
   // Same as before.
}
else {
   ...
   // Changed from CLIENT_REQUEST to UNSPECIFIED.
   events.add( createResumeEvent( DebugEvent.UNSPECIFIED ) );
}

By doing so, this bug is solved.

However, I have noticed that CThread.suspendByTarget() only sends a suspend event for the current thread, i.e. it does not send suspend events for all other threads with UNSPECIFIED detail, as is "recommended" by 158100. It works anyway, i.e. all threads appear as suspended in the debug view. But could this be a side effect of some other operation? Shouldn't CDT follow the pattern as described in 158100 to be on the safe side? If we would do so, we would add the following to CThread.suspendByTarget():

if ( getCDIThread().equals( suspensionThread ) ) {
   // Same as before.
}
else {
   // New else statement that sends a suspend event with UNSPECIFIED
   // detail for all other threads except the suspension thread.
   fireSuspendEvent( DebugEvent.UNSPECIFIED );
}

One other strange thing is that when you switch from one thread to another and do a step operation, CDT will fire a resume event with STEP detail for the previously selected thread (which is wrong) and not the newly selected thread. But when the first step operation finishes, CDT fires a suspend event with STEP_END detail for the newly selected thread (which is right). Howewer, all subsequent step operations will result in the correct flow of events, i.e. a resume event with STEP detail for the newly selected thread and resume events with UNSPECIFIED detail for the others followed by a suspend event with STEP_END detail for the newly seclected thread (but not suspend events with UNSPECIFIED detail for the others as descibed above).

It still seems to work but it is strange that the first step operation on a newly selected thread behaves differently and possibly erroneously. In an earlier conversation on the CDT mailing list I think Mikhail Khodjaiants said that CDT does NOT get notified when the user selects a new thread in the debug view and thusly does NOT issue a -thread-select MI command for that thread. Instead, if I remember correctly, Mikhail said that CDT finds out the selected thread when doing the first operation on the newly selected thread. But in that case, the first step operation on a newly selected thread would not behave like this.

All in all, it seems that the one-liner change in CThread.resumedByTarget() that I described above in combination with the patch for 158100 does solve this bug. Mikhail, if you agree with this fix, can you apply it to CDT 3.1.2 and CDT 4.0?

Stefan Bylund wrote:

The good news is that I think I have found the real reason for this problem and a solution. I traced all events sent to org.eclipse.debug (in
org.eclipse.debug.internal.ui.viewers.update.EventHandlerModelProxy.handleDebugEvents())
and noticed that when you select another thread and singlestep it, CDT will send a Resume/StepOver event for the _previously_ selected thread (and not the currently selected thread) and when the step is finished CDT will send a Suspend/StepEnd event for the actually selected thread. 
Obviously, org.eclipse.debug doesn't handle this well and I'm not sure it should. I believe that CDT should make sure that the Resume/StepOver event it sends is for the thread that is actually selected in the GUI, not for any previously selected thread.

As I understand there are two levels of targets and threads in CDT:

* org.eclipse.cdt.debug.mi.core.cdi.model.Target (ICDITarget) and
  org.eclipse.cdt.debug.mi.core.cdi.model.Thread (ICDIThread).
  It is the ICDITarget that keeps track of which ICDIThread is
  current.

* org.eclipse.cdt.debug.internal.core.model.CDebugTarget (ICDebugTarget) and
  org.eclipse.cdt.debug.internal.core.model.CThread (ICThread).
  It is the ICThreads themselves that know if they are current or not
  while the ICDebugTarget is the parent container for them.

When you select a thread in the Debug View, the corresponding ICDIThread will be made current in its ICDITarget before a resume is performed. 
However, this is not true for the ICThreads. The ICDIThreads and ICThreads are not in sync with each other with respect to current thread status.

One fix for this is to make sure that each time a ICDIThread is made current the corresponding ICThread is also made current. However, I'm not sure that this is really needed in practice.

Another, easier, fix for this is to change the current thread check before ICThreads are resumed (i.e. when it really matters) to make sure that we report a Resume/StepOver event for the correct thread.

Below is a tried and tested patch for the second fix in
org.eclipse.cdt.debug.internal.core.model.CDebugTarget.resumeThreads()
and org.eclipse.cdt.debug.internal.core.model.CThread.resumedByTarget():


--- CDebugTarget.java.org       2007-01-26 14:37:17.000000000 +0100
+++ CDebugTarget.java   2007-01-26 15:56:00.000000000 +0100
@@ -643,7 +643,15 @@
