This patch makes CDebugTarget.resumeThreads() and
CThread.resumedByTarget() behave the same way as
CDebugTarget.suspendThreads() and CThread.suspendByTarget(), which also relies on the underlying ICDIThread to determine current thread status.

I have had problems with writing a multi-threaded program that demonstrates this problem on Linux. My main problem is that if I have a sleep(), pthread_cond_wait(), or similar wait operation in a thread and switch to that thread I can't issue a step operation since I'm blocked deep down in the implementation of sleep() or whatever and a step operation is not possible (it complains about the stack frame boundaries).

See bug 144432 for background information.

When DirBundleFile.getEntry is called for a directory then it should return a FileBundleEntry which ends in '/'.  Consider the following calls.

DirBundleFile dirBundle = new DirBundleFile(new File("somebundledir"));
BundleEntry binWithoutSlash = dirBundle.getEntry("bin");
BundleEntry binWithSlash = dirBundle.getEntry("bin/");

This will result in two BundleEntry objects that have different names ("bin" and "bin/" respectively).  The BundleEntry interface does not have an isDirectory method on it.  Some assumptions have made that entries with names ending in '/' are directories.  We should either:

- add an isDirectory method to BundleEntry or ...
- update the javadoc to state that directory entries must end with '/' and update DirBundleEntry to return a name ending in '/' if the entry is a directory.

